Using a status label/interrupt event to start or end java thread

(Before using this method we have to know these two points very correctly:
1.the thread.run() sometimes contain the block methods, just like sleep(), so in this kind of condition, the jvm cannot 
stop the thread instantly, so we could use a try to contaion all the code that may cause a block of the thread, and as we 
want to stop the thread, we could use a interrupt() method to make the blocked thread throw a interruption exception. And 
as we go into the catch block, we may use to make the label status changed. And the key point is as it is in a while block,
once the while judgement is changed, the block will soon be solved and the whole thread will stop

2.the volatile define is to make the status alway read in the real memory, with out using the registry. So, when in some 
concurrency situations, when multiple threads want to read one state, the state should be defined as a volatile so as to
make sure the state is sync)

Sample java files:

ThreadDrinkTea.java
ThreadSampleMain.java
ThreadWatchingTV.java

/*
Sample Thread For Testing Start And Stop Running
*/
public class ThreadSampleMain {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		System.out.println("Main Tread Start");
		ThreadDrinkTea drink = new ThreadDrinkTea();
		ThreadWatchingTV watch = new ThreadWatchingTV();
		drink.startDrink();
		;
		Thread.sleep(10);
		drink.stopDrink();

		System.out.println("drinking tea finished" + !drink.isAlive());

		watch.startWatch();
		Thread.sleep(10);
		watch.stopWatch();

		System.out.println("watch TV finished" + !drink.isAlive());

	}
}

/*
Sample Thread Drinking Tea
*/
public class ThreadDrinkTea extends Thread {
	volatile boolean run = false;

	@Override
	public synchronized void run() {

		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		while (run) {
			System.out.print("I am drinking tea/n");
		}
	}

	public void startDrink() {
		run = true;
		super.start();
	}

	public void stopDrink() {
		run = false;
	}

}

/*
Sample Thread Watch TV
*/
public class ThreadWatchingTV extends Thread {
	volatile boolean run = false;

	@Override
	public synchronized void run() {

		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		while (run) {
			System.out.print("I am watching tv/n");
		}
	}

	public void startWatch() {
		run = true;
		super.start();
	}

	public void stopWatch() {
		run = false;
	}

}

